				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">65 Child of Bertoxxulous 4000 78 / 59 / 59 Bash, Kick, Quad Attack?, Dual Wield, Enrage, Lifetap, Fearless 
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
4000 (base hp's) + 1405 (Virtue) + 544 (Focus of Soul) = 5949 hp's
<br />

<br />
If the stamina from the focus adds any hit points, that's just a bit over 6k, but requires full buffs.  IF a mage is on hand to give the pet a girdle and weapons, that'll be around 6.5k max the pet can possibly have.  Depending on how many hit points any focus item the necro has, it *could* very well push 7k at this point, but that would require full group buffs and a friendly mage.  Most groups are very wary about having a single pet as a MT.  I suppose if the necro had pet FD and pet discipline he could pull off some impressive pulls and guarantee his pet would have aggro at first, but that's about all I can conclude.  Hit point wise, he is equivalent to our air pet.  From talking to necro friends and watching this pet's performance, I doubt he's a superior tank though.    
<br />

<br />
Consequently if you want to be flashy to a group, you could use Rathe's Son and have them fully buff him.  With Virtue, Focus if Soul, Girdle of Magikot, etc., our mound of rubble can hit 7349 hit points.  He does a decent job tanking with that amount of hit points, and a pet focus only magnifies the result.<br />_________________<br />-<a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=222062" taret=_blank>Sage Booperbustle Tinkermeister</a>
<br />
Arch Convoker of Solusek Ro
<br />
<a href="http://www.furiouspantaloons.org"><i>Furious Pantaloons</i></a></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
